sec.p:
The rapid development of modern portable electronic products and electric vehicles has greatly fostered the development and remarkable progress of lithium‐ion batteries.[

1
, 
2
, 
3

] All‐solid‐state batteries (ASSBs) with inorganic ionic conductors, or solid electrolytes (SEs), are promising candidates to address safety issues and increase energy density.[

4
, 
5
, 
6

] Among inorganic compounds, lithium (Li)‐rich sulfides, and halides have been extensively investigated as potential SEs due to their properties, which include rapid Li‐ion mobility and excellent deformability. The primary objective in solid‐state electrochemistry research is to enhance lithium‐ion conductivity. Owing to significant research efforts, sulfide superionic conductors have been successfully developed, demonstrating notably high lithium‐ion conductivities. For example, Li10GeP2S12,[

7

] Li9.54Si1.74P1.44S11.7Cl0.3,[

8

] Li9.54[Si0.6Ge0.4]1.74P1.44S11.1Br0.3O0.6
[

9

] sulfides give 10 mS cm−1‐level RT ionic conductivities, already exceeding that of liquid electrolytes (≈5 mS cm−1 assuming a lithium transference number of 0.5). Halides display generally lower ionic conductivity than sulfides, but many of them also demonstrate a superionic conductivity of above 1 mS cm−1, such as Li3YBr6,[

10

] Li3InCl6,[

11

] Li2In1/3Sc1/3Cl4.[

12

] They possess a wider electrochemical stability window and superior cathode compatibility compared to sulfides. ASSBs assembled with sulfide and/or halide SEs displayed excellent kinetic performance over a wide temperature range.

The practical application of these advanced SEs relies on mass production, which is a big challenge. The mechanochemical reaction is the most commonly utilized method in a laboratory setting for the synthesis of sulfide and halide SEs, in which reagents are sealed in jars and milled with grinding media (balls) at room temperature (RT) until the target phase is achieved. In this process, chemical reactions occur under mechanical forces (mechanochemistry) that are caused by collisions between the milling balls and reagents.[

13

] This method is notably straightforward and can reduce waste generation by eliminating the use of solvents. However, it typically necessitates an extended duration to attain the desired separation efficiencies, ranging from several hours to multiple days. For example, the Li9.54[Si0.6Ge0.4]1.74P1.44S11.1Br0.3O0.6 sulfide SE with the record conductivity was prepared by an initial ball milling for 40 h, followed by ≈10 h of annealing. The Li3YBr6 halide SE (1.7 mS cm−1) was mechanochemically synthesized with planetary ball milling for 50 h, followed by a period of heat treatment. Based on a new mixed anion strategy, LiNbOCl4 exhibits ionic conductivity up to 9.1 mS cm−1 at RT after 40 h of the ball‐milling process.[

14

] Interestingly, the structure of Nb‐based SEs has a partially amorphized crystalline structure or completely amorphous materials after the ball milling process, as was recently discovered for the Li2O:NbCl5 and LiCl:NbCl5 systems with Li+ conductivity higher than 4 mS cm−1 at RT, which were synthesized within 24 and 144 h, respectively.[

15

]

Furthermore, the processes occurring within planetary ball mills are highly intricate. It has been observed that prolonging the mechanochemical reaction is not always beneficial for improving ion transport in SEs. Moreover, excessive ball milling is likely to introduce local disorder or structural relaxation into SEs, which is associated with decreased ionic conductivity.[

16
, 
17

] Thus, it is essential to elucidate the intricate structural evolution during mechanochemical synthesis of SEs, specifically, to identify the rate‐determining step(s). This is particularly intriguing and vital for the optimization of the mechanochemical process to accelerate the formation of the target conducting phase while simultaneously preventing over‐reaction. Previous studies have revealed the evolution of ionic conductivity and the size/shape of SE particles throughout the mechanochemical reaction.[

18

] The ability to produce particles of a specific dimension represents a key advantage of mechanochemistry, enabling precise modification of material properties and a substantial enhancement of battery performance.[

19

] Nevertheless, the time‐resolved atomic‐scale alterations in the crystal structure of mechanochemical reactions remain inadequately characterized.

The niobium‐based SEs were synthesized by ball milling from a stoichiometric ratio of xLiOH:NbCl5 (x = 0.75–1.05) to determine the optimum Li content in a formed composite. The ionic conductivities of cold‐pressed LixNbOxCl5‐x (LNOC) pellets were assessed by the AC impedance method using Li+‐blocking SS/LNOC SE/SS symmetric cells (Figure S1a, Supporting Information). The Nyquist plot shows one slash starting with a characteristic negative value of the imaginary impedance, which is a characteristic feature of superionic conductors.[
14 , 15 , 20
] The results of multiple repeated electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS) were fitted using the equivalent circuit model, which has been applied to provide a quantitative analysis of the impedance changes (Figure S1b,c and Table S1, Supporting Information). The calculated values of ionic conductivity are presented in Figure
1a. The LNOC powder of x = 0.9 exhibits the remarkable superionic conductivity of 1.02 × 10−2 S cm−1 at 30 °C, which represents the highest value for oxyhalide materials synthesized via the one‐step ball‐milling method.[
14 , 20 , 21 , 22
] The electronic conductivity of LNOC SE obtained by chronoamperometry using the SS/SE/SS symmetric cell was 7.03 × 10−9 S cm−1, which is significantly lower than the ionic conductivity and indicates a poor conductor as given in Figure S2 (Supporting Information). The unique combination of properties, such as superionic conductivity and low electronic conductivity, observed in LNOC SE can reduce side reactions in the ASSB system, in particular, enhancing interfacial stability and improving cycling performance.[
23
]

The EIS results were obtained over a temperature range of −40 °C–80 °C to calculate the activation energy (Figure S3a,b, Supporting Information). At low temperatures, the Nyquist plot exhibits a semicircle followed by a slash. The EIS data were fitted using the equivalent circuit in Figure S3c,d (Supporting Information), with the corresponding fitted values detailed in Table S1 (Supporting Information). The Arrhenius plots and their associated Nyquist plots are presented in Figure 1b and Figure S3 (Supporting Information), respectively. It is remarkable that the ionic conductivity of LNOC SE remained above 1.03 × 10−3 S cm−1 at low temperatures down to −20 °C, and at even lower temperatures of −40 °C, the ionic conductivity was still maintained at 5.14 × 10−4 S cm−1, which is applicable in commercialized Li‐batteries operating under such conditions. The LNOC conductor exhibits a relatively lower activation energy of 0.25 eV, which aligns with the characteristics of the superionic conductor.[
7 , 8
] In comparison, the LiNbCl6 compound with a single anion was also synthesized by the ball milling method, but demonstrated a lower ionic conductivity of 4.59 × 10−7 S cm−1 at 30 °C, accompanied by a high activation energy over >0.5 eV. This comparison underscores the advantages offered by mixed anion chemistry.

Figure 1с illustrates the Arrhenius plot of the superionic LNOC SE compared with representative Li‐ion SEs reported so far. For example, sulfide SEs such as Li9.54Si1.74P1.44S11.7Cl0.3, Li6.6Si0.6Sb0.4S5I, and Li10GeP2S12 exhibit ionic conductivities of 2.5 × 10−2 S cm−1, 1.48 × 10−2 S cm−1, and 1.2 × 10−2 S cm−1 at room temperature (RT), respectively.[

7
, 
8
, 
24

] The oxide‐based Li7La3Zr2O12 conductor with Al‐doping demonstrates an ionic conductivity of about 2.63 × 10−4 S cm−1 at 25 °C, while Li3Zr2Si2PO12 shows 3.59 × 10−3 S cm−1 at 20 °C.[

25
, 
26

] Halide electrolytes exhibit the ionic conductivity of >10−4 S cm−1 at RT, with materials such as Li3Y(Br3Cl3),[

27

] Li3ScCl6,[

28

] Li3YBr6,[

10

] Li3InCl6
[

11

] and Li2ZrCl6
[

29

] presenting ionic conductivity around 4.5 × 10−4 S cm−1 at 30 °C. Furthermore, various Li‐M‐X compounds, where M = represents Al,[

30

] Mg[

31

] or Zn[

32

] possess poor ionic conductivities less than 10−4 S cm−1 at RT. The present LNOC SE is a superionic conductor in the halide family solid‐state electrolyte with ionic conductivity >10−2 S cm−1 comparable to that of sulfide electrolytes (Table S2, Supporting Information).

The dependency of ionic conductivity on the grinding time of LiOH and NbCl5, ranging from 1 to 60 h, was obtained through 8 intermediate steps with reloading of the initial raw material for each step (Figure 1d). During the initial 3 h of the mechanochemical process, the ionic conductivity exhibits a substantial increase from 1.1 × 10−4 to 5 × 10−3 S cm−1 at RT (see Table S3, Supporting Information). Moreover, the ionic conductivity continues to rise significantly with prolonged increasing milling time, surpassing 1.02 × 10−2 S cm−1 at RT after 24 h. Beyond this duration, extending the milling time to 60 h results in only minor fluctuations in conductivity. Interestingly, the optimized composition achieves a conductivity of 10−2 S cm−1 within 24 h of the ball milling process, in contrast to LiNbOCl4, which reaches 9.7 × 10−3 S cm−1 after 40 h. In addition, Nb‐based oxyhalide synthesized using Li2O as a precursor in the system Li2O:NbCl5 SEs demonstrates a lower ionic conductivity of 4.47 × 10−3 S cm−1 following a 24 h ball milling process. In both cases, the presence of LiCl impurities in the LiNbOCl4 and Li2O:NbCl5 materials restricts ionic conductivity.[
14 , 15
] It is evident that optimizing the composition of the solid electrolyte material can significantly enhance conductivity, as clearly demonstrated by comparison with other halide electrolytes synthesized via the ball milling method.

The primary coordination environment of the mixed‐anion solid electrolyte LNOC surrounding Nb was further elucidated using ATR‐FTIR and Raman spectroscopy. As shown in Figure S14 (Supporting Information), the ATR‐FTIR spectrum of the LNOC SE exhibits two distinct absorption bands at 800–850 and 580–750 cm−1, which correspond to the vibrations of the Nb─O─Nb bonds in the structure.[
33
] The band at 800–850 cm−1 can be attributed to the symmetric stretching of the Nb─O─Nb bonds in a nearly linear (collinear) configuration, which is characteristic of polyhedra bonded to each other at an angle close to 180°. In turn, the band at 580–750 cm−1 can be associated with asymmetric vibrations or stretching in locally distorted Nb─O─Nb bonds arising from the mixed anionic environment (O/Cl), local defects, or partial amorphization. Such distortions lead to a deviation of the Nb─O─Nb angle from linearity, which reduces the frequency of the corresponding oscillations. Thus, the spectral features in the 600–850 cm−1 region reflect the presence of both ordered linear Nb─O─Nb fragments and locally distorted areas in the material, confirming the existence of structural heterogeneity. In addition, Raman spectra exhibit Nb─O/Cl coordination, which is created by the combination of Nb─O─Nb niobium‐oxygen double bond vibrational mode at 770 cm−1 and chloride double bond vibrational mode Nb─Cl─Nb at 397–340 cm−1, respectively (Figure S15, Supporting Information).[
34 , 35 , 36
] The removal of hydrogen from the synthesized product is confirmed by the results of 1H nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectroscopy of LNOC SE in combination with LNC SE (Figure S16, Supporting Information). In addition, FTIR spectroscopy of the gas released during the mechanochemical reaction in the ball milling jar was obtained, and it was confirmed that H from raw material LiOH reacted with NbCl5 and released HCl gas, which was detectable at around 2800–2900 cm−1 (Figure S17, Supporting Information).[
37
]

The XRD patterns of synthesized LNOC SEs give broadened main reflections, as shown in Figure S18 (Supporting Information). The broad reflections from the low crystallinity of the LNOC materials are usually observed in samples prepared by the mechanochemical process.[
10 , 11
] The refinements were performed by the Rietveld method of the GSAS II software package.[
38 , 39 , 40 , 41
] Based on the detailed discussion by W. G. Zeier et al., we selected the I4/m space group to identify the crystal structure of the prepared LNOC SE.[
42
] A combination of synchrotron X‐ray diffraction (SXRD) and powder neutron diffraction (PND) was used in a joint refinement to reliably determine both atomic positions and occupancies (Figure
2a–c). Following the guidelines outlined in their work, we determined that the synthesized materials fall within the composition range of 0.75 ≤ x ≤ 1.05 for LixNbOxCl5‐x, as supported by the (110)/(101) peak intensity ratio of ≈0.796(1) and the lattice parameters of 8.92 ≤ a ≤ 8.97 Å and 3.96 ≤ c ≤ 3.98 Å. Table S4 shows the refined results that fit both X‐ray and neutron diffraction patterns. From the refinements, we observe a more stable trend compared to those previously reported findings,[
42 , 43
] with the thermal displacement parameter for oxygen falling within an acceptable range. However, the O2− substitutes for Cl− exhibits a significantly larger thermal displacement, suggesting increased bond distortion when O2− occupies this position instead of Cl−. This substitution likely causes a deviation from linearity in the Nb─O/Cl─Nb linkage (1.97 Å), which in turn affects the geometry of the surrounding octahedral motifs. Because the partial substitution of chlorine by oxygen introduces compositional disorder at the bridging anion site, the nearest Nb–Nb interatomic distance (6.64 Å) oriented along the (111) direction has changed accordingly.

The electrochemical stability window of LNOC SE was evaluated by cyclic voltammetry measurements using Li‐In/Li6PS5Cl/LNOC/LNOC+CNT cells, as shown in Figure S24 (Supporting Information). The argyrodite sulfide electrolyte Li6PS5Cl (LPSC) exhibits an ionic conductivity of 9.78 × 10−3 S cm−1 at RT (Figure S25, Supporting Information), which is used as an additional protective layer to prevent direct chemical reaction between LNOC material and Li‐In alloy.[

47

] Carbon nanotube CNT (30 wt.%) was added to the working electrode to improve electronic conductivity, which allows a more accurate determination of the electrochemical stability window.[

48

] The LNOC SE shows a high oxidation potential of 4.42 V vs. Li+/Li and a reduction voltage for the Nb5+ cation at 3.32 V vs. Li+/Li, which is consistent with computational results for Nb‐based solid electrolytes.[

49

] This result corresponds to the fact that this material is not resistant to the reduction of Li. Hence, the LNOC SE shows an electrochemical stability window from 3.32 to 4.42 V vs. Li+/Li that can be used with high‐voltage oxide cathode material for high‐energy‐density ASSBs.

After returning to 0.5C, the capacity can stay at 140.8 mAh g−1. During long‐term cycle tests at 0.5C, the specific capacity gradually decreases, and the capacity remains at the level of 76.5% after the 400th cycle, as plotted in Figure 5c. In addition, the long‐term cycle performance of LNOC ASSBs was tested at a high current density of 2C, and the initial specific capacity reduced from 112.5 to 78.8 mAh g−1 after 500 cycles (Figure 5d), which corresponds to a capacity retention of 70.1% and a high average Coulomb efficiency of 99.9%. The results showed that the applied pressure of 200 MPa for ASSBs significantly improved the cycling stability and capacity retention compared to lower pressures (see Figure S26, Supporting Information). Accordingly, it can be concluded that the applied pressure of 200 MPa significantly enhances electrochemical performance, which is crucial in maintaining solid–solid contact and reducing interfacial resistance during cycling. Afterward, the evolution of impedance during cycling at a current density of 2C was investigated to understand the degradation of the interface (as shown in Figures S27 and S28, Supporting Information). These results highlight the importance of optimizing ASSB with LNOC SE by improving the stability of the sulfide/oxyhalide interface or replacing the sulfide with a halide electrolyte that is stable to the anode materials.[
14 , 51
] The results show that oxygen not only improves ion transport by changing the local environment of LiOCl5 and NbO2Cl4, but also stabilizes the material electrochemically due to stronger bonds with oxygen, reducing the maximum energies of interfacial reactions between SE halides and SE sulfides.[
52
]

For the scalable implementation of halide‐based SEs, it is essential that SEs exhibit excellent ionic conductivity and enable seamless integration into all‐solid‐state batteries, but also demonstrate robust moisture stability and low cost.[
29
] Currently, In and Zr‐based halides are the most moisture‐resistant.[
53 , 54 , 55
] Therefore, to evaluate the moisture‐sensitiveness of LNOC SE, we tested oxyhalide SEs in comparison with one‐anion halide SEs, such as Li3InCl6 and Li2ZrCl6, at different relative humidities (RH = 5%–7% and 10%–12%) for 1, 6, and 12 h, respectively. Li2ZrCl6 SE demonstrated superior moisture stability at RH 5%–7%, followed by LNOC and Li3InCl6, exhibiting residual conductivities of 36.5%, 25.5%, and 9.6%, respectively (Figure S32 and Table S6, Supporting Information). The obtained results correlate well with the calculated maximum interfacial reaction energies of potential chemical reactions between representative halides SEs and H2O (Figure S33, Supporting Information), confirming that LZC has stronger bonds than LNOC and LIC. While LIC SE contains In3+ centers prone to hydrolysis and formation of In–OH compounds under humid conditions, the LNOC structure is characterized by Nb‐based oxychloride domains, where Nb─O bonds promote partial covalency and increase lattice stability. The presence of oxygen in the structure probably passivates the hydrolysis pathways, stabilizing the coordination environment of niobium, thereby suppressing the release of Cl− and Li+ into aqueous media. To investigate the degradation behavior of the LNOC solid electrolyte, time‐dependent XRD analysis was performed for 80 min, allowing identification of the decomposition products formed during this period (see Figure S34, Supporting Information).

In light of the significance of cost in practical applications, a comparative analysis of the expenses associated with LNOC SEs was conducted in relation to other conventional sulfide, halide, and oxide SEs.[
22 , 29
] As shown in Figure S37 and Table S7 (Supporting Information), the results show that the cost of LNOC SE is comparable with that of widely used commercial SEs and also has the lowest cost compared with the anion‐mixed SEs, which have an ionic conductivity close to 10−2 S cm−1 at RT. In summary, the high ionic conductivities and excellent cycling performance over a wide temperature range, good moisture stability, and promising commercialization demonstrate the high potential for practical application of Nb‐based oxyhalide SE in high‐performance halide ASSBs.

Bond Valence Site Energy (BVSE) Calculations used to investigate the migration of Li ions are based on the SoftBV program, using the single crystal structural model as input and the SoftBV bond valence parameter set developed by S. Adams.[
43 , 45
] Lithium‐ion site energies were calculated for a dense grid of points with a resolution of 0.1 Å covering the crystal structure using the transferable Morse‐type softBV force field. Li‐ion diffusion pathways are identified with the regions of low bond valence site energy. The LNOC structure determined from powder neutron diffraction was used as the input structure for the BVSE calculations. BVSE maps with an EBVSE(Li) constant iso‐surface energy over the global minimum indicate Li‐ion diffusion pathways. BVSE calculations have been used to study a wide variety of ion conductors and show good agreement with experiments and calculations.
